# üêß Linux Practice Questions 

## Topic
Linux Basics, Files, Directories, Users, Groups, and Viewing Commands

## üßë‚Äçüíª Section 1: User Management (1‚Äì15)

1. Create a normal user named `user10`.
2. Create another user named `user20` with a specific UID.
3. Verify that both users exist in the system.
4. Check the UID and GID of `user10`.
5. Set a password for `user10`.
6. Force `user10` to change the password at next login.
7. Lock the account of `user20`.
8. Verify whether `user20` is locked.
9. Unlock the account of `user20`.
10. Change the login shell of `user10`.
11. Add a comment field to `user20`.
12. Rename `user10` to `user_one`.
13. Verify that the UID remains unchanged after renaming.
14. Check the home directory of `user_one`.
15. Delete `user20` without removing its home directory.

---

## üë• Section 2: Group Management (16‚Äì25)

16. Create a group named `groupA`.
17. Create another group named `groupB`.
18. Add `user_one` to `groupA`.
19. Add `user_one` to `groupB` as a secondary group.
20. Verify group membership of `user_one`.
21. Change the primary group of `user_one`.
22. Remove `user_one` from `groupB`.
23. Rename the group `groupA` to `teamA`.
24. Verify the new group name exists.
25. Delete the group `groupB`.

---

## üìÅ Section 3: Directory Operations (26‚Äì35)

26. Create a directory named `project`.
27. Inside `project`, create directories `src`, `bin`, and `logs`.
28. Navigate to the `src` directory.
29. Move back to the `project` directory using a relative path.
30. List all directories in detailed format.
31. Create a nested directory structure `data/input/raw`.
32. Verify the complete directory tree.
33. Attempt to remove a non-empty directory using `rmdir`.
34. Remove an empty directory using `rmdir`.
35. Remove the entire `project` directory recursively.

---

## üìÑ Section 4: File Operations (36‚Äì50)

36. Create a file named `fileA.txt`.
37. Create multiple files `fileB.txt`, `fileC.txt`, and `fileD.txt`.
38. List all files including hidden files.
39. Display file details using long listing format.
40. Copy `fileA.txt` to `fileA_backup.txt`.
41. Move `fileB.txt` to another directory.
42. Rename `fileC.txt` to `fileC_old.txt`.
43. Delete `fileD.txt`.
44. Attempt to delete a directory using `rm` without options.
45. Delete a directory using recursive remove.
46. Create a file and update its timestamp.
47. Verify file size and modification time.
48. Remove multiple files using a single command.
49. Recreate deleted files.
50. Verify which files currently exist.

---

## üìñ Section 5: File Viewing Commands (51‚Äì60)

51. Create a text file named `notes.txt`.
52. Add at least 10 lines of text to `notes.txt`.
53. Display the entire file using a single command.
54. Display the file with line numbers.
55. View the file using a paging command.
56. Exit from the paging view.
57. Display only the first 5 lines of the file.
58. Display only the last 5 lines of the file.
59. Append additional lines to `notes.txt`.
60. View only the newly added lines.

---

## üîç Section 6: Navigation and Information (61‚Äì70)

61. Display your current working directory.
62. Navigate to your home directory using a shortcut.
63. Navigate to `/etc` using an absolute path.
64. Return to the previous directory.
65. Identify the difference between absolute and relative paths.
66. Display the currently logged-in users.
67. Display only your username.
68. Check login history of the system.
69. Verify users with UID greater than or equal to 1000.
70. Cross-check user information from `/etc/passwd`.
